[According to the follow-up report No. 1 submitted by the Bulgarian authorities to the OIE on Tue 19 Apr 2016, 4 of the 6 new outbreaks are in the Haskovo province, while the other 2 are in 2 different provinces, namely the (already affected) Stara Zagora province and the hitherto unaffected Plovdiv province. An interactive map showing all 9 LSD outbreaks in Bulgaria since the start of the event is available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapEventSummary&reportid=20063. - Mod.AS]

******
[2] Vaccination contemplated
Date: Tue 19 Apr 2016
Source: Focus Information Agency [edited]
http://www.focus-fen.net/news/2016/04/19/404131/dr-trifon-tsvetkov-it-is-necessary-to-carry-out-vaccination-of-all-susceptible-animals-to-lumpy-skin-disease.html


"It is necessary to carry out timely and rapid vaccination of all susceptible animals to the viral disease called nodular dermatitis (lumpy skin disease). First, it must be done so in the area where outbreaks have been found," according to the chairman of the Supervisory Board of the Bulgarian Veterinary Union, Dr Trifon Tsvetkov, in an interview with FOCUS News Agency.

According to him, in view of the emerging distribution of the disease, the current measures are no longer sufficient. Dr Tsvetkov said that at first, vaccination would be carried out throughout South Bulgaria. "The funds will be provided by the state," he said.

--
communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns
