[The apparent decision (or advice?) to apply lumpy skin disease vaccination in Bulgaria is not surprising. As anticipated (see 20160419.4167379), a stamping out policy has meagre chances of success in a country invaded by the lumpy skin disease virus from adjacent borders of endemic countries (in this case, both Greece and Turkey could have been the source of infection).

According to OIE's WAHID archive, the summary of the Bulgarian event, as of 19 Apr 2016, is as follows:

Total outbreaks = 9 (Submitted)
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 366 / 12 / 0 / 366 / 0

Of the 9 recorded outbreaks, 6 were reported from Haskovo, 2 from Stara Zagora and one from Plovdiv province. According to an update in the same Bulgarian News Agency "Focus" dated 20 Apr 2016, the lumpy skin disease spread continues: "537 animals from 13 farms have been affected by the disease. The affected districts are Haskovo, Stara Zagora and Plovdiv." See at http://www.focus-fen.net/news/2016/04/20/404213/bulgaria-officially-allocates-bgn-15-to-fight-lumpy-skin-disease.html.

In case vaccination is applied in Bulgaria, this might be the same vaccine applied in Greece, namely a freeze-dried, live attenuated virus (Neethling strain) vaccine. A similar vaccine has recently been applied in Israel (see ProMED-mail post 20150926.3672096). As reported in another posting (20150929.3676992), CODA-CERVA (Belgium) in partnership with the Pirbright laboratory (UK) were coordinating a project on the comparison of lumpy skin disease vaccines. The project was planned to address 6 different vaccines, including live attenuated lumpy skin disease vaccines, live attenuated sheep pox or goat pox vaccines, and newly developed inactivated vaccines. It would be helpful to be informed of the advance attained in the mentioned comparative project, a live attenuated vaccine. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4171323,81.]
